tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the close of the Second World War, when industrialized nations faced serious trade and financial imbalances, delegates from forty-four countries met in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, in order to reconstruct the international monetary system. In this volume, three generations of scholars and policy makers, some of whom participated in the 1944 conference, consider how the Bretton Woods System contributed to unprecedented economic stability and rapid growth for 25 years and discuss the problems that plagued the system and led to its eventual collapse in 1971. The contributors explore adjustment, liquidity, and transmission under the System; the way it affected developing countries; and the role of the International Monetary Fund in maintaining a stable rate. The authors examine the reasons for the System's success and eventual collapse, compare it to subsequent monetary regimes, such as the European Monetary System, and address the possibility of a new fixed exchange rate for today's world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBusiness. 0aInternational finance. 0aMonetary policy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  awwii, world war, postwar, wartime, time period, history, historical, national, nations, industrial, industrialized, industry, trade, finance, financial, new hampshire, monetary, money, economics, economy, 1940s, conference, system, systemic, collapse, contemporary, modern, exchange, essay collection, anthology, reform, adjustment, mechanism.1 aBergsten, C. Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Edward M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBordo, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4